</A> <B>Posted by <A HREF="http://www.monkey.org/~timothy">timothy</A>  on  Thursday July 20, @01:00PM</B><BR>
<FONT size=2><B>from the web-researcher-breaks-speed-of-light! dept.</B></FONT><BR>
Last Tuesday <a href="http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=00/07/06/1850219&mode=nested">you asked</a> <a href=mailto:mingo@redhat.com>Ingo Molnar</a>, Red Hat kernel hacker, about the means by which his TUX Web server recently achieved such <a href="http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=00/07/05/0211257&mode=nested">fantastic results</a> in <a href ="http://www.spec.org/osg/web99/results/res2000q2/web99-20000626-00054.html">SpecWeb99</a>  . He was kind enough to respond with at-length answers addressing licensing, the reality of threads under Linux, the realism of benchmarks, and more. Thanks, Ingo! 

