</TR></TABLE><A HREF="http://slashdot.org/search.pl?topic=debian"><IMG SRC="http://images.slashdot.org/topics/topicdebian.gif" WIDTH="54" HEIGHT="63"
	BORDER="0" ALIGN="RIGHT" HSPACE="20" VSPACE="10" ALT="Debian">
</A> <B>Posted by <A HREF="http://roblimo.com/">Roblimo</A>  on  Monday July 10, @02:00PM</B><BR>
<FONT size=2><B>from the moving-on-to-new-projects dept.</B></FONT><BR>
Ian Murdock started the Debian Project in 1993 and was its leader until 1996. Now he's president and CEO of <A HREF="http://www.progenylinux.com/">Progeny Linux Systems</A>, a company working on a Debian-based system called <A HREF="http://www.progenylinux.com/now/">Linux NOW</A>. (<A HREF="http://www.perens.com/">Bruce Perens</A> is chairman of the company's board of directors, so the place is obviously as Debian as a commercial entity can get.) Please post your questions for Ian below. We'll forward 10 of the highest-moderated questions to him by e-mail and run his replies as soon as he gets them back to us. 

<!-- begin story_link block -->
